    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="803"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d803">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control (Rumania)/7–2045:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 803<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-20">July 20,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>79. <persName corresp="#p_SBGCTVR1">General Schuyler</persName> has telegraphed
                        <gloss target="#t_War1">War</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> outline of Soviet “new procedure” for
                    second period <gloss target="#t_ACC1">ACC</gloss> Rumania which is in
                    substantially same form as that for Bulgaria<note n="1" xml:id="d803fn1">See
                            <ref target="frus1945Berlinv01#d309">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>,
                            document No. 309</ref>.</note> (Re <gloss target="#t_Dept1"
                    >Dept</gloss>’s 30 July 16<note n="2" xml:id="d803fn2">Not printed. See <ref
                            target="frus1945Berlinv01#d310fn1">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>,
                            document No. 310, footnote 1</ref>.</note>). It contains similar article
                    providing for “discussion” prior to issuance of directives on questions of
                    principle. We view this procedure as unsatisfactory since it does not provide
                    for prior agreement by British and American representatives. The comparable
                    article in the Hungarian proposal (See Tel 286 July 13 from Budapest to <gloss
                        target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> repeated to you<note n="3" xml:id="d803fn3"
                        >Not printed. See <ref target="#d794fn6">document No. 794, footnote 6</ref>.
                        For text of the proposal referred to, see <ref target="#d796">document No.
                            796</ref>.</note>) appears more satisfactory. We believe it highly
                    important that every effort be made to obtain agreement at Potsdam on this
                    fundamental matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>[<persName corresp="#p_GJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                        </persName>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
